The Labour Party is no longer a group of people with different views.
The party is intolerant of people expressing their opinions
When the Momentum activists in my party voted to reprimand me, I was not surprised.
After all, I am a member of a group of Labour MPs who have recently been told that they are not welcome, all because of their own opinions.
My parliamentary colleague Joan Ryan was treated similarly because she opposed anti-Semitism.
In my case, the request for reprimand was based on a difference of opinion between me and Jeremy Corbyn.
The differences concerned the importance of responsible economic policy, national security and Europe. Ironically, Jeremy Corbyn opposed the position of previous leaders on these issues.
In Friday’s announcement of the Labour MPs’ meeting in Nottingham East, one could read: “We want the meetings to be open and productive.”
In my eight years as a Labour MP, most of the General Committee's Friday afternoon meetings looked like this.
Unfortunately, many meetings today are held in a different way, and the promise of a “kinder and gentler” policy has long been forgotten, if ever it was remembered.
It is becoming more and more obvious that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party. Each opinion is evaluated in terms of compliance with the leadership of the party.
It all started shortly after Jeremy Corbyn took over as chairman. My colleagues, who seemed to me to have similar views, began to expect me to change direction and take positions that I would not have agreed with before. They concerned issues such as national security or the EU's single market.
After every public appearance – regardless of the content – I encounter on social media attacks calling for the rejection of the nomination, the condemnation of centrism or the abandonment of the Labour Party.
This is not just my experience.
I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments directed at me are rather political in nature.
I admire the professionalism and determination of colleagues who experience sexist or racist treatment every day, but do not avoid further action.
One of the most disappointing aspects of the current policy is the transition to an agenda of insulting others.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
In fact, we are no longer a group of people with different views. With every request for a “vote of no confidence” and every change in the rules of choice, the party’s worldview is narrowed.
Over the past two years, I have been repeatedly told not to stoop and keep quiet about certain issues, and then everything would be “okay.”
That’s not why I took up politics.
Since joining the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student as a result of Margaret Thatcher’s government’s negligence that led to the collapse of my school class, I have strived to provide a better quality of public service to those in need – both as a local councilor and as a minister.
I never hid my convictions, even during the last election campaign.
Everyone in Nottingham East knew my position and the differences of opinion with the party authorities.
To those who supported Friday's proposal, I cannot understand the desire to waste time and energy on the issue of my loyalty to the Labour leader in the face of an impending Brexit that will harm households, businesses and public services.
The most important message, however, is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents (both Labour and the rest): I am proud to serve you. I promise that no threats of rescission or ad hoc political objectives will deter me from acting in accordance with my convictions and in the best interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East.
