"The sea belongs to us": Bolivia, deprived of access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen its way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol the area around the Navy base in La Paz.
There are blue flags flying from public buildings.
In the ports of the navy from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, there is the following motto: “The sea is ours by law.
It is our duty to get him back.”
In a landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in the bloody conflict over 19th-century resources is still vivid, like a dream of re-navigating the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps the highest in several decades. Bolivia is awaiting a judgment from the International Court of Justice, due to be issued on 1 October after a five-year trial.
“Bolivia’s actions are gaining momentum. Residents are unanimous, optimistic and counting on a favorable verdict,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians across the country will be watching the International Court of Justice meeting together. They hope the Hague-based organization will acknowledge Bolivia's claim and, after decades of fruitless talks, Chile will have to enter into negotiations to grant the country independent access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic president who faces a controversial re-election battle next year, is also hopeful in Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he vowed at the end of August.
Some analysts, however, say that the chances of a favourable ruling for Bolivia are small and that even a favourable decision would make little difference.
The United Nations body based in The Hague does not have the authority to grant Bolivia the territory of Chile. It also stipulated that it would not affect the arrangements for possible talks.
According to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law, the decision of the International Court of Justice will be issued six months after the presentation of the final arguments. Such a short time shows that the case "was not complicated".
Unfortunately for Bolivia, the past four years have been able to push the country away from its goal.
"The issue of access to the sea has been appropriated by the current Bolivian administration," Paz Zárate said.
Morales’ relentless rhetoric deprived Chileans of any remnants of goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but this will be very difficult in the face of the situation.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, former president and representative of Bolivia in The Hague, disagreed with the view that the court's decision-making process was extremely fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia "a unique opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile" and the possibility of "ending a 139-year period of disputes with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — used the subject of access to the sea as part of a political game.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
“A verdict is an excellent opportunity to convince ourselves that we have to deal with the past.”
