John Edward: language skills necessary for the world's citizens
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their academic achievements – in 2018 they could boast of further excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), the schools, attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland, aim to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and to indicate their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector with the ability to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to another person in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages occupy the first place in league rankings, with the highest pass rates for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received a higher A grade in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received an A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as elective subjects, is conducted in the same scope as STEM (Scientific Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) subjects within the framework of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 per cent of job vacancies were caused by a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for the start of their professional careers.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring language skills,
Lifelong learning skills, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future —regardless of the career path taken.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit rate of 15%.
That is why investing in foreign language teaching is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, every school will be different in terms of the languages it teaches.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of the child, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from, which will be taught by specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed – no matter what the future holds for them.
Currently, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a wide range, diversity and level.
That's just the way it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
