North Korea says "strongly no" to unilateral disarmament without confidence.
North Korea’s foreign minister said Saturday during a speech at the United Nations that the failure to lift sanctions only deepens North Korea’s lack of confidence in the United States and there is no way the country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site of nuclear tests and committing to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
“But we don’t see any concrete response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security, and in such circumstances, there can be no unilateral disarmament of North Korea.”
While Ri echoed well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s reluctance to take a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking action gradually, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization, as it has in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent U.S. president and North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump promised security guarantees for North Korea.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (1950–1953), but the U.S. mission announced that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing signing a ‘declaration of end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is the dream of people who behave ignorantly towards us.
The problem, however, is that the failure to lift sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which the U.S. leader spoke about earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, he drew attention to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea was a party to denuclearization, not the United States, then there was no such deadlock in the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.”
The tone of Ri’s speech was completely different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles into U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim Jong Un a “rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened the “total destruction” of North Korea, praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but also said there was still much work to be done and said that until North Korea was stripped of its nuclear weapons, sanctions would not be lifted.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not set a time limit, saying, “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue and be sustained until we find full, final and verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear program and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ri outside the UN General Assembly forum and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month in preparation for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his latest visit cannot be called a success.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, after which North Korea condemned him within hours for “placing gangster demands.”
North Korea pledged this month at a meeting with Moon Jae-in that it would dismantle the missile test site and the nuclear complex if the United States took “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim Jong Un had told him that the “appropriate measures” he cared about were the security guarantees Trump pledged in Singapore and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course on a sufficiently long rest
A new course at Harvard University, which took place this year, provided all students with more sleep, which was aimed at combating the growing macho culture, which consists of learning by “all-night caffeine-fueled students”.
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
To create the course, he was inspired to give a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
At the end of the speech, a girl came up to me and said, “Why am I being told this now that I’m in my final year of college?”
She said that no one had ever told her about the meaning of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which took place for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help achieve good academic and sports performance, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the course was decided to introduce after it was found that students suffered from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes an image of a dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know — just as everyone has a right to know what the health effects of smoking are.”
A culture of pride in “all-night science” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means a growing problem of lack of sleep.
“Providing enough good quality sleep should be a ‘secret weapon’ for students to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even avoid gaining weight because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry,” he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped develop the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a campus-wide course.
The next step, according to him, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar program of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm to remind them when to go to sleep and when to get up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to problems falling asleep.
