Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our Sunday Morning edition of Almanac: September 30, 1882 — 136 years ago... the day the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, which eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has become part of both science and pop culture, as in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, in which these seemingly unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans performed:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter that’s used to locate radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you will hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radioactive minerals.”
Evans: “Now you hear something!”
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name has survived to this day.
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “see” hostile cells.
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach Immune System to ‘See’ Hostile Cells and Destroy Them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize enemy cells as part of treatment.
This method is to extract the immune cells from the patient and change them in the laboratory.
Then they can "see" the protein common to many cancers. Then they are re-injected into the body.
The trial vaccine has shown promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
One woman treated with a vaccine that taught the immune system to recognise hostile cells had ovarian cancer that had gone away for more than 18 months.
The method involves removing the immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then re-injecting these cells into the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the US National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results indicate that this vaccine is working very well.
HER2 “drives the growth of several types of cancers,” including breast, ovarian, lung and colon cancers, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to locate cancer cells worked in the treatment of a kind of leukemia.
