What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed in any way to reducing poverty?
Next Saturday, the Global Citizen Festival will be held in New York City, an annual music event boasting an impressive lineup of stars and an equally impressive mission – to end poverty in the world.
The seventh Global Citizen Festival will visit tens of thousands of people coming to the Central Park Great Lawn to not only enjoy the performances of such stars as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to support the realization of the most important goal of this event, which is the elimination of extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international group of anti-poverty activists by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless it was decided to purchase a VIP ticket), concert participants had to complete a series of tasks or “actions” such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or other meaningful activities to help raise awareness of the goal of ending poverty.
But what successes can Global Citizen boast of in the perspective of the 12 years remaining to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a good way to convince them to take action, or another case of so-called “clictivism” when people feel they are doing something important by signing an online petition or tweeting?
Global Citizen says it has seen more than 19 million “actions” by supporters of the campaign since 2011, aiming to achieve a wide variety of goals.
These actions have helped spur world leaders to announce commitments and regulations worth more than $37 billion, which are expected to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements resulting from its activities, under which at least $ 10 billion has already been paid or financed.
The group estimates that the measures have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
