The creator of the World Wide Web is planning to launch a new Internet in order to compete with the platforms of Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the creator of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that creates on the basis of the open source platform — Solid — owned by Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which individuals have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of Inrupt was "world domination".
“We have to do it now,” he said, referring to the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid platform technology to allow people to create their own “webshop with personal data” or POD.
It can include contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify available in one browser and at the same time.
A unique feature of an online store with personal data is that it completely depends on the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide resources, processes, and relevant skills to help make the Solid platform available to all people.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world have been able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether to make a total change that will overnight turn all of their business models upside down.
“Don’t ask for permission.”
In a post on the Medium platform, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to deliver trade and ecosystem energy to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been heavily involved in the net neutrality debate.
Announcing Inrupt Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely excited to be thinking about the next era in network development,” added Berners-Lee.
Bernard Vann: Order of the Cross of Victoria during the First World War
The memory of the only clergyman of the Church of England, who was awarded the Victoria Cross as a combatant during World War I, was commemorated 100 years later in his hometown.
Lt. Col. Bernard Vann was decorated on 29 September 1918 for his attacks on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never knowing that he had been awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said the unveiling of the stone on the 100th anniversary of his grandfather’s award was “extremely symbolic.”
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lt. Col. Vann led his battalion through the Canal Saint-Quentin "in a very thick fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns".
He then hurried to the line of fire and, with "greatest courage" led her forward, then single-handedly attacked the field guns' position, disabling three of them.
Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I would never have been able to handle, but something humble at the same time.”
Together with his brother, Dr. James Vann, he laid a wreath at the end of a parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honored to be able to take part in the parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is reflected in the support he receives from many people."
