His son has the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father didn’t accept that he was dying, and one of the last things he asked was whether they already had tickets to the 2012 London Olympics — he wanted to take place in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You’re not going to be with us to be in the front row, Dad,’” he said.
“I held his hand when he stopped breathing. Only when he stopped breathing and died did I realize that he was not invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley took part in the 2012 Olympic Games and won bronze.
“I knew that was what I had dreamed of all my life — jumping into the water in front of a crowd of people at the Olympics — it was the best feeling possible,” he said.
It also inspired him to choose the first song, "Proud" by Heather Small, which accompanied him in the run-up to the Olympics and continues to give him goose bumps.
