New German warship delayed again
The German Navy’s newest frigate should be commissioned in 2014 to replace aging Cold War-era warships, but it won’t be until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the main ship of the new frigate of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but due to problems that arose after delivery, it was necessary to make changes to this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
Of course, they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as technological solutions that prevent detection, ensuring, among others, the reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic traces.
Other important features include longer periods between maintenance periods — it should be possible to operate new frigates for up to two years away from their home ports.
However, the constant delays mean that these modern warships, which are designed to allow the Germans to respond to situations abroad, will be obsolete at the time of starting their service, notes Die Zeit.
