The software flaws were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships were to be manned by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the size of the older Bremen-class frigates.
It also turned out that the ship is much too heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the possibility of the Navy to carry out future modernizations.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty equipment, the cost of the entire project — including crew training — also becomes a problem.
