He also said that this problem has increased over time due to the decommissioning of old units without the provision of replacement ships.
In addition, he expressed his dissatisfaction with the fact that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wurttemberg class could be included in the navy.
The National Trust overhears the secret life of bats
A new study conducted at a property in the Scottish Highlands aims to show how bats use the landscape to obtain food.
The findings are expected to shed new light on the conservation of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The research, led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will focus on common and small dwarfs, as well as brown long-eared bats and red-nosed bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
At key locations around the property, special recorders will be deployed to keep track of bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out field tests using portable detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings is aimed at determining the frequency of signals sent by bats and the behavior of individual species.
Then a habitat map and a report will be developed to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that have an impact on perches and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly glue and some chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles in their path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly carry out tests, inspections of the nest, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organisation has even established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve on the grounds of the Three estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
David Thompson, the manager of the estate, says that it is ideal territory for bats.
“Threave has a great area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and great habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns when it comes to bats. The work we do here and on other estates will help us to better understand what they need in order to thrive.”
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance work on the estates, as the unintentional destruction of one nest can kill up to 400 females and young, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected —it is illegal to kill, harass, or disturb them, as well as to destroy their foals.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species we don’t even know how their populations are doing.”
