Brexit: UK ‘would regret for all time’ car manufacturers’ departure
LONDON (Reuters) - Britain would “regret it forever” if it were to lose its status as the world’s leading carmaker after leaving the European Union, business minister Greg Clark said on Wednesday.
He added that he was “concerned” when a Toyota UK representative told the BBC in an interview that if the UK left the EU without a deal, production at a factory in Burnaston near Derby would be temporarily halted.
“We need a deal,” Clark said.
A spokesman for the Japanese carmaker said the effects of delays at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit could lead to job cuts.
The Burnaston plant, which produces the Auris and Avensis, produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“In my opinion, if the UK leaves the European Union at the end of March without a deal, then there will be a halt in production at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s managing director at Burnaston.
Other British carmakers fear leaving the EU without an agreement on how cross-border trade works, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
For example, BMW is going to close its Mini car factory in Oxford a month after Brexit.
The main concerns, according to car manufacturers, relate to the risks associated with the supply chain in the event of the UK leaving the European Union without a deal.
Toyota’s production line operates on a “just-in-time” basis, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in both the UK and the EU for custom-made cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, there could be obstacles at the border, which industry officials say could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
Toyota said it would not be able to survive more than a day without deliveries to its Derbyshire plant, halting production.
Clark said Theresa May’s plan for a future relationship with the EU was “precisely designed to avoid border controls”.
“We need an agreement. We want to achieve the best possible agreement that will not only allow us to enjoy the current success, but also allow us to take advantage of this situation,” he said on BBC Radio 4’s Today programme.
“The statements made by not only Toyota but also other manufacturers show that we need to be able to continue what has been a very efficient set of supply chains.”
Toyota was unable to say for how long production would be halted, but warned that in the long run additional costs would reduce the plant’s competitiveness, leading to a reduction in employment.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at the Burnaston plant for 24 years and is a board member of the union’s trade union organization Unite, said the union’s members are increasingly concerned: “I know from experience that if jobs are eliminated, they will never be reinstated.
