Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
According to official reports, at least 384 people have died as a result of the powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday.
Because of broken communications, rescuers were unable to obtain any information from the Donggala cabupate, which is located north of Palu, closer to the epicenter of the 7.5-magnitude earthquake.
More than 16,000 people were evacuated from Palu after the disaster.
Here are some important information about the city of Palu and the Donggala Cabubate on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of Central Celebes, a province located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island. According to estimates in 2017, they were inhabited by 379,800 people.
When the earthquake and tsunami occurred, the city was celebrating the 40th anniversary of its foundation.
Donggala is a kabupaten (administrative unit lower than the province) extending along the northwest coast of the island for more than 300 km.
It is estimated that in 2017 it was inhabited by 299,200 people.
The main branches of the economy of Central Celebes are fishing and agriculture, which developed especially in the coastal cabupaten of Donggala.
Another source of income for the province are nickel mines, but they are mainly located in Morawali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, earthquakes and tsunamis have struck Palu and Donggala several times over the past 100 years.
In 1938, the tsunami that hit Donggala killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes.
In 1996, a tsunami killed nine people in western Donggali.
Indonesia is on the seismically active Pacific Ring of Fire, which is why earthquakes occur there quite regularly.
The biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake that struck the west coast of Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26, triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: In late March and early April, the west coast of Sumatra was hit by a series of powerful earthquakes.
Hundreds of people have died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: In southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, there was a 6.8-magnitude earthquake, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra.
As a result, more than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake struck one of the islands of Mentawai off the coast of Sumatra. It triggered a tsunami wave as high as 10 meters, which destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya kabupaten in Aceh province, causing devastation and panic among people who still remembered the devastation caused by the 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time there was no tsunami, but the collapsed buildings killed more than 100 people.
2018: Large earthquakes hit the tourist island of Indonesia, Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on its northern side.
They caused the destruction of thousands of homes and brought temporary trouble to thousands of tourists.
