“We cry when we’re angry,” Gloria Steinem told me 45 years later.
“That’s pretty common, isn’t it?”
She added: “I was helped tremendously by a woman who was a manager at a company. She said that she also cries when she’s angry, but she made up a way that when she gets angry and starts crying, she says to the person she’s talking to, ‘You probably think I’m sad because I’m crying.
I'm angry.
And he's still doing his thing.
I thought it was genius.”
Tears are acceptable as a vent of anger in part because they are fundamentally misunderstood.
One of my most vivid memories from one of the first jobs in a male-dominated office was when I began to cry one day out of inexpressible rage. An older woman —a cool manager I had always been a little afraid of— grabbed me by the neck and led me up the stairs.
“Never let them see you cry,” she said.
“They don’t know you’re angry.
They think you're sad, and they're glad you're done."
Patricia Schroeder of the Democratic Party, then a member of Congress from Colorado, worked with Gary Hart on his presidential campaign.
In 1987, when Hart was caught with his mistress on a boat called Monkey Business and withdrew from the race, frustrated to the limit, Patricia realized that she could actually consider running for president on her own.
“It wasn’t a deliberate decision,” she told me, laughing, 30 years later.
“There were seven other candidates running and the last thing they needed was another one.
Someone described the situation as “The Snow Queen and the Seven Dwarfs.”
As the campaign had been going on for a long time, Schroeder was behind in raising funds and promised herself that she would not enter the race unless she raised $2 million.
It was a battle doomed to lose.
She discovered that some of her followers, who gave the men $1,000, only had $250 for her.
“Do they think I have any discounts?” she wondered.
During her speech, in which she announced that she would not be running a formal campaign, she was so filled with emotion—gratitude to those who supported her, frustration at a system that made it so difficult to raise money and appeal to voters, not delegates, and anger at sexism—that her voice stuck in her throat.
“You’d think I had a nervous breakdown,” recalls the reaction of the press.
“You’d think I’d be sponsored by Kleenex.
I remember wondering what they'd write on my gravestone.
"She was crying?"
What are the benefits of Beijing's economic war between the United States and China?
The salvos that started the economic war between the US and China were deafening, and while the battle is still ongoing, in the long run the conflict between these countries could be beneficial to Beijing, experts say.
The first warning was issued this year by U.S. President Donald Trump, who imposed tariffs on key Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation came this week after the introduction of new tariffs on $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) worth of goods, resulting in the taxation of half of all goods entering the US from China.
Each time, Beijing reciprocated in nature, recently raising tariffs on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods from five to ten percent.
China is determined to respond to every U.S. strike, and it doesn’t look like the world’s second-largest economy is about to give up.
Forcing Washington to back down means accepting the demands, but publicly bowing its head to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
But experts say if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressure from the U.S. trade war could strengthen China in the long run, reducing the interdependencies between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision made in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions to unleash economic chaos in one of the countries is in fact much more dangerous than previously admitted by observers,” said Abigail Grace, an Asia researcher at the Center for New American Security think tank.
Syria's foreign minister says it is 'ready' for refugees to return
The government says Syria is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for help in rebuilding the country, which has been devastated by more than seven years of war.
In his speech to the UN General Assembly, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“The situation on our soil is now more stable and secure thanks to progress in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
In an effort to restore normalcy, the government continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists.
All conditions have already been met for refugees who have had to leave the country because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods to return to it voluntarily.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million people have left Syria since the war began in 2011.
Another six million people still living there are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to accept help in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid offered by the countries that sponsored the insurgency.
Europe seals victory at Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup, beating the US team 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National in the suburbs of Paris.
On European soil, the United States has lost for the sixth time in a row and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the trophy when, under the leadership of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, it received 14.5 points, which were needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who was not doing well for most of the tournament, hit the ball from the stand straight into the water at the 16th hole of PAR3, thus giving the match to Francesc Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shined through all the rounds and became one of the four players who, since 1979, when this tournament was held for the first time in its current format, managed to get a 5-0-0 result.
American Jordan Spieth was eliminated 5&4 by the lowest ranked player from Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, who occupies the highest position in the world ranking, lost two holes before the last hole with the Englishman Ian Poulter, for whom this may have been the last tournament of the Ryder Cup.
The European with the most wins in the Ryder Cup was Spanish Sergio Garcia, who has already taken part in eight such tournaments and scored 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but I can’t help myself today.
