Flowering information — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota, the density of plankton decreases
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decline in plankton densities in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of variegated bloom has been reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It stretches along about 209 kilometers of coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
Blooms can be found about 16 kilometers off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in a smaller number of places.
It was also found in Pasco County.
Last week, there was an average concentration of plankton off the coast and in the waters of Pinellas County, low to medium on the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high in the coast and in the waters of Sarasota County, natural to medium in Charlotte County, natural to high in Col County and on the water.
Cases of respiratory irritation are still reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Last week, however, they were not reported in north-west Florida.
